<paragraph blockId="103.[192,1440,451,1403]" pageId="103" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis box="[240,370,1347,1371]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="102">Etymology</emphasis>
—This species is named 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik &amp; Holzenthal" authorityYear="2017" box="[675,866,1347,1371]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Mortoniella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="103" pageNumber="102" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[675,866,1347,1371]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="102">M. triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the shape of the dorsal phallic spine of the male, which is distinctly trianguloid in appearance, as viewed laterally.
</paragraph>
